Moved from the US with to Europe with my dog, assuming the process is similar from Canada. You need to get your vet to complete export papers that comply with EU pet import standards e.g. vaccinations, microchip, approved breeds, etc. The airline checks the paperwork, often times the EU customs doesn't review at all. Once in Europe, most vets can convert that into a pet passport, allowing you to travel within the EU freely with your pet. Mediterranean/Southern countries like Portugal, Spain, Italy have some additional suggestions for mosquitoes etc. My dog now has a Greek and Portuguese passport lol
